{The next two examples are from the same chapter: double rounds drama, not
drawing drawing positions and not winning winning ones. For some reasons, I
thought this game should very soon and 'very easy' become a draw. I couldn't
have been more wrong.} 58... bxa4 {An immediate draw would have been achieved
after} (58... Rh4+ $5 59. Kc5 Rh5 $1 60. Kd6 Rh6+ 61. Kd5 Nc3+ $11) 59. Rxa4
Ra3 60. Ra5 Ke7 {Understandable move but a clear cut drawing continuation
would have been:} (60... Rxa5 61. bxa5 Na3 62. Kc5 Kd8 $11) 61. Nc4 Rb3 (61...
Rxa5 {doesn't work anymore due to} 62. bxa5 Kd7 63. Kd3 {and the knight is
trapped on b1.}) 62. b5 Nc3 63. b6 Kd7 {What could be more natural than
bringing the king closer to that Speedy Gonzales pawn? But somehow it does
feel a bit too late for Black to regain control.} 64. Ra7+ Kc6 (64... Kc8 {
doesn't help either} 65. Nd6+ Kb8 66. Rb7+ Ka8 67. Kc4 Rb1 {looks cute but
there is no stalemate} 68. Kxc3 Rb3+ 69. Kc4 Rb4+ 70. Kc5 $18 {White has now
the option of taking that rook with the knight on either b5 or c4, whichever
Black prefers.}) 65. Rc7+ Kb5 66. Nd6+ Kb4 67. Rxc3 {Somehow I still have
troubles believing how fast a seemingly equal position can go downhill. And
yet, the Russian GM finished on the 2nd place with 7/11.} (67. Rxc3 Rxc3 68. b7
$18) 1-0

