{Needless to repeat what I already mentioned in all my previous articles but I
have to do it, for accuracy's sake. Novendra is the next Indonesian big talent
capable of finding new and newer rabbits in his hat, winning or drawing
'hopeless' positions. That is not mere luck but a sign of his fighting and
defending abilities. Three pawns up - that should be a rather straight forward
win for White, right?} 67... Ne4 68. Nd1 {1-0 would have been the most likely
outcome had White played} (68. d6 {instead.} Nxd6 69. Nd5+ Kf7 70. Nxb6 $18)
68... Nd6 69. Nc3 {The winning margin is still there but the advantage starts
slipping on a psychological level.} ({By offering something, White gains much
more in return} 69. Nf2 Nxc4 (69... Nxf5 70. Ne4+ Kg6 71. d6 Nh6+ 72. Kf3 Kf7
73. Nxc5 $18) 70. Ne4+ Kf7 71. d6 $18) 69... Kg7 70. Na4 {Sacrifices must be
made indeed, for a higher cause, but the quiet} (70. Kf3 {would have worked
too.} Nxc4 71. Ne4 Na3 72. f6+ Kf7 73. d6 $18) 70... Nxc4 71. Kg5 Kf7 72. f6
Nd6 73. Nxb6 {Black has only one pawn left but a very stubborn one.} (73. Nc3 {
was the final boarding call for a win.} c4 74. f5 {and Black just ran into a
multiple choice of equally bad continuations.} Nb7 (74... Kf8 75. Kf4 Nf7 76.
Ke4 $18) 75. Ne4 Kf8 76. Kf4 Kf7 77. Ke5 $18) 73... c4 74. Nd7 c3 75. Ne5+ Kf8
76. b6 c2 77. Nd3 Kf7 78. Nc1 {When I was following the game online, I thought
that somehow the result must be wrong or maybe the transmission stopped
prematurely. Optically, I couldn't believe that Black can draw in such an
exceptional way! There is no way forward for White at this point.} 1/2-1/2

